review_blob: Bomber to snifter. Pours a chocolate brown, with a creamy brown head. Aroma is roasted malts and vanilla. Taste is roasted malts, vanilla, cinnamon, and a hint of coffee.
Pours a pale yellow, no head. Aroma is honey and a slight vanilla. Tastes is honey, slight vanilla and oak, with a slight bourbon like aftertaste
beer_name: Superstition Lagrimas de Oro (Tears of Gold) Mead

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Pours a deep dark brown with chocolate colored head. Aroma is alcohol, oak, and chocolate. Taste is coffee, chocolate, bourbon, oak. Slightly sticky texture.
beer_name: Lost Abbey Box Set: Track #10 (Bat out of Hell)

review_blob: Bomber to tulip. Pours a hazy reddish brown. Thin, lacey off white head. Aroma is toffee, alcohol, vanilla, and oak. Taste is tannins, toffee, charred oak, vanilla, and tree sap.
Bomber to tulip. Pours a dark reddish brown with a pale brown head that dissipates quickly. Aroma is tart, leather, vinegar, cherries, with a slightly sugary candy-like sweetness.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Bomber. Pours a hazy orange with a thick yellowish white head. Aroma is resinous hop bitterness. Taste is sticky hop bitterness with a slight tropical fruit aftertaste.

2014 bottle, poured into tulip. Pours a slightly hazy reddish brown, with an orange coloring on the edges. Has an thick orange brown head. Aroma is sweet red wine, cherries, sour, and funk. Taste is tart, brett funkiness, cherries, wine.
Bomber to snifter. Pours a pale orange gold. No head. Aromas of honey, orange, and saffron. Taste is saffron, honey, orange juice, with a hint of hops.
Nitro 12oz into nonic pint. Pours a dark brown with a thick, creamy beige head. Aromas of vanilla, chocolate, and roasted malts. Taste is creamy, sweet, roasted malts, chocolate and vanilla.
beer_name: Left Hand Wake Up Dead Imperial Stout

review_blob: Bomber to tulip. Pours a dark dark brown with a thick mocha colored head. Aroma is sweet pumpkin, chai tea, roasted malts, and dessert spices. Taste reminds me of pumpkin pie, with significant roastiness and a slight alcohol burn. Has a slightly sticky texture.
beer_name: Stone Imperial Russian Stout - Chai Spiced

review_blob: 11.2oz to tulip. Pours a slightly reddish dark brown with a thin beige head. Aroma is cardamom, cinnamon, and chocolate. Taste is roasty, bitter, and has a heavy cardamom taste.

Enjoy by 4.20.15. 12oz into tulip. Pours a golden orange with a thick white head. Aroma is resinous, slightly herbal hop notes. Taste is crisp and bitter. Not as good as some of the other batches, but at the same time better than others.
Growler to Tulip. (Thanks Treebute!!) Pours a bright golden orange with a thin white head. Aroma is floral and grassy hop notes. Taste is pleasantly bitter.
Tap. Pours a bright reddish purple with a wispy pinkish white head. Aromas of apples. Taste is apples, sour blueberries, and oak. Totally could
12oz to snifter. Pours a very pale golden color with a lackey white head. Aroma is pear and agave nectar. Taste is apple, pear, and a slight barrely note.

Bomber into snifter. Pours a hazy golden orange with a lacy white head. Aroma is sour raspberries with a slight hint of vinegar. Taste is sour, with a decent amount of raspberry flavors, and a consistent pucker.

Bomber into tulip. Pours a bright yellow, almost like white wine. Aroma is sweet, with aromas of honey, vanilla, and a slight aroma of what I can only describe as Play-Doh. Taste is sweet honey with a significant vanilla presence that smooths out the honey sweetness before it becomes cloying. Has an aftertaste of pineapple.

Bomber into tulip. Pours a dark pinkish orange with no head. Aroma is honey with a slightly fruity note. Taste is significant prickly pear, with a lingering honey sweetness. Has a slightly sticky mouthfeel
12oz to tulip. Pours a dark golden orange with a thick yellowish off white head. Aroma is dank, tropical fruits, and hop bitterness. Taste is dank bitterness, with a crisp semi-piney bite.
Release 5. Bomber into tulip. Pours a bright golden orange, with a thin white head. Aroma is funky, white wine. Taste is tart, funky, white wine, with a slight fresh grape fruitiness.
beer_name: Epic / Crooked Stave Elder Brett Saison - Brett Golden Ale

review_blob: 12oz to tulip. Pours a dark, chocolate brown, with a thin, light brown head. Aromas of chocolate, and roasted malts. Tastes of roasted malts, biscuity, and chocolate.
beer_name: Bells Planet Series: Jupiter - The Bringer Of Jollity

review_blob: 12oz to tulip. Pours deep black, with a chocolate brown head. Aromas of roasted malt, chocolate, bourbon,and oak barrels. Taste is roasty, chocolate, charred oak, bourbon, and an underlying alcohol heat. Has a lingering, syrupy presence that
12oz to tulip. Pours black, with a thin coffee colored head. Aroma is dry, oak barrels, chocolate, and roasted grains. Taste is chocolate, whiskey, oak barrels, and rye spiciness. Thanks Tom!
12oz to tulip. Pours a reddish orange with a thin white head. Aroma is tart, lactic acid, and cranberry juice. Taste is sweet, tart, berries, with an aftertaste of cranberry juice. Thanks Tom
beer_name: New Glarus Thumbprint Series Cran-bic Ale

review_blob: Bottle to tulip. Pours a blackish brown, with a latte colored head. Aromas of Tequila, oak barrels, roasted malts, and chocolate. Tastes of Tequila, lime juice, charred oak barrels, chocolate. Is initially sweet, and has a bitter aftertaste.
Bottle to tulip. Pours a brownish black with a thin khaki colored head. Aroma is charred oak, roasted malts, and caramel. Taste is thick, roasty, chocolate, and oak.

(Bottled August 15, 2013) Bomber to tulip. Pours a dark, leathery red with a thin, light brown head. Aroma is acidic, with faint berry notes and a tart, lemony finish. Taste is sour, acidic, with lemon, berry, and tart rhubarb. For some reason this beer feels strangely chalk to me.
Bomber (Thanks Tom) to tulip. Pours a clear brownish red with a thin khaki colored head. Aroma is strawberries. Taste is strawberry and tart rhubarb. Very very sweet.

Bomber, (Thanks Tom) to tulip. Pours almost the same color as cranberry juice, with a thin khaki colored head. Smells like fresh apple, cherry, leather, and a fruity tartness. Taste is tart, sweet, and is simultaneously reminiscent of apple juice, cranberry juice, and tart cherries. The wild fermentation blends perfectly with the tartness of the cherries and the fresh fruityness of the apples and cranberries.

Growler poured to tulip. Pours a chocolate brown with a thin khaki colored head. Smells like a chocolate porter, with a slight coconut smell. Tastes like an Almond Joy, with strong flavors of chocolate and coconut, and an underlying nuttiness.
beer_name: Oskar Blues / Shamrock Death By Coconut

review_blob: Tap. Pours a golden orange, with a thick slightly yellow head. Aroma is tropical hops. Taste is tropical bitterness, and is exceptionally well balanced.

Bomber to tulip. Pours a dark brown, with a slightly reddish, coffee colored head. Smells meaty, with a slight locker room smell. Tastes of Nail polish remover, roast malt, with a slightly spicy aftertaste.

12oz bottled October 25, 2012, poured into tulip. Pours a yellowish gold with a thin white head. Lots and lots of sediment. Aroma is tart sour apples. Taste is green apple, vinegar, and a cloying sweetness.

12oz, bottled Nov 19, 2013, to tulip. Pours a dark purple/ berry red with a pinkish purple head. Aroma is sour, sweet berry. Taste is tart, with huge berry taste. A heavy, tart jam like sweetness hangs out in your mouth for quite a while after taking a sip. A slightly acidic sourness sits lurking behind the jam.

12oz into goblet. Pours a deep, chocolate brown. Head is frothy and chocolate colored, looks like I was blowing bubbles into a glass of chocolate milk. Aroma is Roasted coffee, with a little bit of milk chocolate. Tastes of coffee, chocolate, with a slightly malty dryness from the lactose.
12oz to snifter. Pours a pale yellowish gold, with a white head that fades immediately. Aroma is sweet apples and unripe pear. Taste is sweet apple. I kinda maybe sorta taste pear.

12 oz into tulip. Pours a clear, deep, dark brownish red color. Head is a dark khaki color. Aroma is sweet, with a slight dried fruit note. Taste is sweet and slightly spiced, with a firmish malt backbone.

12oz to tulip. Pours a slightly hazy golden-orange. Has a slight amount of sediment suspended throughout it. Head is white and fades quickly, butt still leaves a good amount of lacing around the side of the glass. Aroma is floral, slightly citrusy, with an underlying sweetness. Taste is very bitter, definitely a palate-wrecker. A tropical fruityness is present underneath the bitterness, and helps to smooth out the residual bitterness. Despite the extreme bitterness, this beer is quite smooth.

Bomber into tulip. Pours a deep, slightly pink-hued crimson. Head is a pale pink, and fades rather quickly. Aroma is very faint, almost floral, sweet raspberry. Taste is raspberries, with a slightly doughy, spicy note from the Belgian yeast. This beer is almost too sweet; it is very similar to Rubaeus , except with a spicy Beligian note. It is basically liquid raspberry candy. Not that thats a bad thing.
12oz into Lagunitas mason jar. Pours an orange-gold color with a sticky off-white head. Aroma is dank, resinous hops. Taste is crisp, dank hop bitterness.

22oz bottled on July 1, 2013. Poured into BP tulip. Pours a deep brown with a chocolate colored head. Aroma is cumin, curry powder, toasted coconut, and a slight coffee roastyness. Taste is chocolaty, coconut, with a slightly herbal spiciness. As it warms up, lime bitterness egins to become more present. Mouthfeel is smooth, and very porter-esque
Can to Tulip. Pours a semi-hazy golden orange color. Fuzzy white head that fades immediately. Aroma is salt and blood orange peel. Tastes of blood orange, briny salt, and a spicy coriander note.
beer_name: Anderson Valley Highway 128 Blood Orange Gose

review_blob: Been holding on to this for a couple of months. 500ml bottle poured into tulip. Pours a hazy gold-tinged red. Head is a light tan color that fades relatively quickly. Aroma is tart, sweet, funky red wine with a hint of dried dark fruits. Taste is tart, with plenty of Brett funkiness. The red wine flavors are present, but not particularly pronounced.

Bomber to tulip. Pours a deep black color, with a coffee colored head that fades rather quickly. Aroma is bourbon, charred oak, and roasted coffee. Tastes of bourbon, oak, malty sweetness, roasted coffee, and rye spiceness.

Bomber into snifter. No head whatsoever. Pours a bright yellow/gold color. Aroma is sweet, honey, and a slight white wine smell. Taste is smooth, sweet, honey, finishing with a pronounced white wine taste. The 13.5% alcohol is well hidden by the sweetness and smoothness of this mead.
beer_name: Superstition Snow on Mount Olympus Pyment

review_blob: Swing-top bomber into snifter. Pours a light golden color. There is no head. Aroma is very light, sweet, honey, and faint tropical fruit. Taste is sweet honey slightly spicy, and mango. The sweetness is nowhere near as overpowering as in other meads, and the mango is almost the dominant flavor. Also, the 15% abv is completely hidden by the tropical sweetness. Mouthfeel is smooth, and similar to actual honey in the way is coats your mouth.

Can, poured into Flute. Pouras a Bright Golden color. Head is thin, white, and fades almost immediately, although there is ample carbonation in this beer. Aroma is tart, funky, and slight sea salt/brine. Taste is salty, sour, and vaguely citrus. Mouthfeel is very effervescent, similar to sweet champagne.
beer_name: Anderson Valley Highway 128 The Kimmie, The Yink, and the Holy Gose

review_blob: 12oz to pilsner glass. Pours a clear golden color. Head is effervescent, thin, white, and lacy. Aroma is grain and slight skunkiness. Taste is skunky, bitter, but has a clean sharp bite. Mouthfeel is smooth and crisp.
Bomber into tulip. Pours a deep, clear red Thin pink head that fades fairly quickly. Aroma is slightly tart, cherries, and a slight vinegar smell, Taste is tart, cherries, and a slight vinegar taste.
beer_name: New Belgium Lips of Faith - Transatlantique Kriek

review_blob: 12oz, poured into tulip. Head is thick, white, and fades after a minute or so. Color is hazy golden. Aroma is sour and funky, with a slight hint of wet straw. Taste is funky, medium sour, with a slightly chalky mouthfeel.
